From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v44 - dce_v8_0 preserve BIOS PLL/timing on Liverpool, dump PPLL state

Supersedes 0017 (v33). Same intent (skip ATOM PLL/timing on Liverpool because
ATOM AdjustDisplayPll/SetPixelClock return zero data even after the v40 ACPI
fix), but adds two things:

  1. Reads all four PPLL register banks (DCCG_PLL0..3 REF_DIV, FB_DIV,
     POST_DIV) and the three PIXCLKn_RESYNC_CNTL registers, dumps them via
     pr_info before doing anything else. After the next boot we'll see
     exactly what BIOS-default PLL state PS4 firmware leaves the GPU in
     when Linux takes over. This is the diagnostic data we've been missing
     when reasoning about the PLL path.

  2. Skips amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_pll, set_dtd_timing, overscan_setup,
     and scaler_setup for Liverpool/Gladius. All four go through ATOM and
     would clobber BIOS-default state with garbage. Only do_set_base
     (framebuffer scanout, direct register writes) and cursor_reset run.

Hypothesis being tested: if BIOS already has the PLL configured correctly
for whatever resolution PS4 boot firmware brought up (most likely 1080p60
since PS4 OS targets that), and we don't touch the PLL or DP TX state,
then attaching our framebuffer should produce visible scanout on HDMI via
the MN864729 bridge.

Possible outcomes:
  A) Display lights up — confirms the kill chain was ATOM clobbering
     BIOS-default PLL/DP-TX state. Future work: replicate the BIOS-default
     PLL programming so we can change resolutions.
  B) Display still dark, but PPLL register dump shows valid dividers —
     the kill is downstream of the PLL (DP TX, DIG encoder, or bridge
     timing). PLL bypass eliminated as a hypothesis.
  C) Display still dark, PPLL register dump shows zeros / garbage — BIOS
     never programmed PPLL on this boot path (kexec from PS4 OS may not
     leave display state intact). Need a manual PLL programmer with
     hand-computed dividers in a follow-up patch.

This patch is intentionally conservative: it READS PLL state, doesn't
WRITE PLL state. We can write hand-computed values in a follow-up once we
know what BIOS gives us.

Replaces the workaround chain v28 fallback + v33 skip with a single,
better-instrumented Liverpool path. The v28 fallback block stays for non-
Liverpool ASICs that may also exhibit ATOM AdjustDisplayPll returning 0.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
@@ -2552,6 +2552,7 @@
 				  int x, int y, struct drm_framebuffer *old_fb)
 {
 	struct amdgpu_crtc *amdgpu_crtc = to_amdgpu_crtc(crtc);
+	struct amdgpu_device *adev = drm_to_adev(crtc->dev);

 	if (!amdgpu_crtc->adjusted_clock) {
 		/* v28: PS4 ATOM BIOS sometimes returns 0 from
@@ -2568,6 +2569,49 @@
 		amdgpu_crtc->adjusted_clock = adjusted_mode->clock;
 	}

+	/* v44 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius): PS4 VBIOS lacks usable ATOM AdjustDisplayPll/
+	 * SetPixelClock data even after the v40 ACPI fix (mutex chain works, but the
+	 * tables themselves return zero). Calling amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_pll/
+	 * set_dtd_timing programs the hardware with garbage and breaks the BIOS-
+	 * default DP TX state that the MN864729 bridge needs to lock onto.
+	 *
+	 * Strategy: skip all ATOM-driven mode_set work, preserve the PS4 boot
+	 * firmware's PLL/timing configuration, and only update what the framebuffer
+	 * scanout needs (those writes don't go through ATOM). Dump current PPLL state
+	 * to dmesg so we can see exactly what BIOS left us with. If the bridge still
+	 * doesn't get signal after this, the issue is upstream of the PLL (DP TX or
+	 * DIG encoder) and not anything mode_set can fix. */
+	if (adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS) {
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL0 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL0_PLL_POST_DIV));
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL1 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL1_PLL_POST_DIV));
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL2 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL2_PLL_POST_DIV));
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PPLL3 (BIOS): ref=0x%08x fb=0x%08x post=0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_REF_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_FB_DIV),
+			RREG32(mmDCCG_PLL3_PLL_POST_DIV));
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool PIXCLK0/1/2 RESYNC: 0x%08x 0x%08x 0x%08x\n",
+			RREG32(mmPIXCLK0_RESYNC_CNTL),
+			RREG32(mmPIXCLK1_RESYNC_CNTL),
+			RREG32(mmPIXCLK2_RESYNC_CNTL));
+		pr_info("dce_v8_0_crtc_mode_set: Liverpool - preserving BIOS PLL/timing, "
+			"framebuffer-only setup (clock=%d kHz, x=%d, y=%d)\n",
+			adjusted_mode->clock, x, y);
+
+		dce_v8_0_crtc_do_set_base(crtc, old_fb, x, y, 0);
+		dce_v8_0_cursor_reset(crtc);
+		amdgpu_crtc->hw_mode = *adjusted_mode;
+		return 0;
+	}
+
 	amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_pll(crtc, adjusted_mode);
 	amdgpu_atombios_crtc_set_dtd_timing(crtc, adjusted_mode);
 	dce_v8_0_crtc_do_set_base(crtc, old_fb, x, y, 0);
